    <title>Combined summary - alternate proposal opt-in miner takes double-spend (Re: replace-by-fee v0.10.0rc4)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T17:42:14.732875+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-February/007538.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In discussions dating back to 2015, Bitcoin experts have warned about the risks associated with relying on zero-confirmation transactions and the potential for double-spending vulnerabilities. Various solutions were proposed, including the use of multisignature notaries as the most practical approach for actual security for unconfirmed transactions. However, some argued that a general-purpose scripting language improvement could eliminate the need to rely entirely on inherently unreliable P2P networking.Despite these warnings, people are still using zero-confirmation transactions for low-value transactions, exposing themselves to potential losses. The consensus is that relying on zero-confirmation transactions is risky and potentially fatal, and users should consider alternative approaches such as multisignature notaries or implementing improvements to the protocol to enhance security.In another conversation from February 2015, Peter Todd discusses the potential risks of relying on zero-confirmation transactions, including the possibility of tainted UTXOs and miners conspiring with double-spending thieves. Todd suggests implementing fidelity bonds as protection against double-spends, but there are questions about how they would function and who would pay out in the event of a double-spend. The discussion also touches on the use of multisignature notaries for high-value transactions with untrusted customers, and the possibility of predicting and pricing risk associated with different types of transactions. Matt Whitlock recounts an incident where a merchant at the Bitcoin 2013 conference lost money due to zero-confirmation transactions that depended on other unconfirmed transactions that never went through. While this risk can be priced in when enough data is available, further investigation into the situation could reveal valuable insights. Overall, the discussions highlight the potential risks and limitations of relying on zero-confirmation transactions in the Bitcoin network, and suggest various solutions such as implementing new signature types or using multisignature notaries for high-value transactions.There is a suggestion in the Bitcoin world to introduce a new transaction type that marks itself as spendable by miners if a double-spend is seen before 1-confirm. This feature would be opt-in and soft-forkable, meaning high-value coins would not be at risk of failure. The aim is to improve practical security of fast confirmation transactions. In the past, there have been instances where merchants have accepted zero-confirmation transactions that depended on other unconfirmed transactions that never confirmed. This resulted in the merchant not receiving payment for their goods. Matt Whitlock suggests tracking the failure rate of zero-confirmation transactions and adjusting prices accordingly to cover expected losses as "there are no payment methods with a 0% fraud rate." He argues that zero-confirmation transactions can work as long as the risk of reversal is measurable and reasonably stable.There is also discussion around whether it is the job of developers to change systems to do something it wasn't designed to do when users use it in ways it was not intended to be used. In an email thread from February 2015, Adam Back proposed exploring ways to improve practical security of fast confirmation transactions rather than deprecating current weaker 0-conf transactions. Peter Todd responded by suggesting implementing this proposal as a general-purpose scripting language improvement, not relying entirely on inherently unreliable P2P networking. He argued that blowing up 0-confirm transactions is not vandalism and provided analogies to explain his point. Finally, he signed off his email as 'peter'[:-1]@petertodd.org.</summary>
